The paper deals with algorithms for exact path problems in edge-weighted digraphs, which are typically studied in the computer science subfield of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The use of Dyck and semi-Dyck labeled paths suggests a connection to computational geometry (cs.CG), as these are commonly used in the study of convex hulls and triangulations. The paper also mentions the concatenation of symbols along a path, which is a topic in discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The study of reachability in digraphs is a topic in both computational complexity (cs.CC) and machine learning (cs.LG), as it is relevant to the design of efficient algorithms and models for decision-making.
